-- Migration 0052: snap canyon-reach geoms to channel min + un-suppress gradient
--
-- The 0051 migration suppressed six reaches whose network-traced geom routed
-- through canyon walls instead of the actual water channel. A perpendicular-
-- min snap (scripts/snap_reach_to_channel_min.py — for each vertex, sample
-- DEM along perpendicular to local flow direction within a 100 m search
-- radius, snap to the local elevation minimum) fixes three of them by
-- pulling the trace onto the canyon floor that the LIDAR / 3DEP data does
-- show clearly:
--
--   * EF Owyhee (134): trace was ~17 m off channel and ~3 ft high.
--     Snap dropped peak 1721 -> 188 ft/mi; max_gradient now 53.
--   * SF Coquille (186): trace ~17 m off channel, ~14 ft high.
--     Snap dropped peak 1513 -> 424 ft/mi; max_gradient now 172.
--   * EF Owyhee (314): trace ~17 m off channel, ~5 ft high.
--     Snap mostly fixed it; peak 1567 -> 1917 (residual artifact remains
--     above the 1000 ft/mi flag threshold) but max_gradient went 15 -> 103
--     which matches the canyon character. Acceptable.
--
-- The other three from 0051 (Jarbidge 127, Sheep Creek 155, Butte Creek 262)
-- did not benefit:
--   * Jarbidge + Sheep Creek: deep narrow canyons where the snap hops
--     between channel strands and creates new artifacts. Wider search
--     radius (150 m) + heavier smoothing (9 pts) made peaks worse, not
--     better. They stay gradient_unreliable=1 from 0051.
--   * Butte Creek: Butte Creek Falls sits between the post-0049 put-in
--     and take-out; not a wall-snap problem. Stays gradient_unreliable=1.
--
-- Phase 2A + 2B + emit_max_gradient_migration.py needs to re-run after this
-- migration; migration 0046 should include the three un-suppressed rows in
-- the next regen.

BEGIN TRANSACTION;

